SIMPLE: chromatic
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Chromatic
<hw>Chro*mat"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>chromaticus</ets>, Gr. <?/, suited for color, fr. <?/, <?/, color;
akin to <?/ color, <?/ skin, color of the skin.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Relating to color, or to colors.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>Proceeding by the smaller
intervals (half steps or semitones) of the scale, instead of the regular
intervals of the diatonic scale.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The intermediate tones were formerly written and printed
in colors.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Chromatic aberration</b></col>. <fld>(Opt.)</fld> <cd>See
<er>Aberration</er>, <er>4</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Chromatic
printing</b></col>, <cd>printing from type or blocks covered with inks
of various colors.</cd> -- <col><b>Chromatic scale</b></col>
<fld>(Mus.)</fld>, <cd>the scale consisting of thirteen tones, including
the eight scale tones and the five intermediate tones.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Chromatical</ent>⟦br⟧
